			      <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				        <p>... past, future and present members ... for the sake of
					well-being and happiness in both worlds and <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">nirvāṇa</foreign> for herself, in
				        	the Great Monastery, at the base of the Great Shrine, ... a stone (pavillion) ... for great community of monks (consisting) of
					renunciants who come from various countries, in the 15th
					year of King Siri-Vīrapurisadatta — may he
					live<!-- AG: or 'rule'? --> one hundred years! —, in the ...
					fortnight of the rainy season ..., in the possession of the
					Aparamahāvinaseliyas, together with a quadrangular compound
					... established ...</p>
			      </div>
			      <div type="commentary">
				<!--[Revision required]-->
				        <listApp>
					          <app loc="5">
						            <lem>vasasatāya</lem>
						            <note>See <bibl>
                        <ptr target="eiad-bibl:Sircara"/>: <citedRange>1</citedRange>
                     </bibl>. This word occurs also in EIAD <ref target="#EIAD0030">30</ref> and <ref target="#EIAD0242">242</ref>. One might at first be tempted to translate  <quote>may he reign one hundred years!</quote>, but <ref target="#EIAD0160">160</ref>, l. 2 <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">vāsasatāyuka</foreign> speaks for the interpretation preferred here.</note>
						            <!-- and in a  Banavasi inscription (Bühler 1885, to be read with note of the Editor [i.e., D.C. Sircar] to Gai 1963-64: 241) deserves a note. Is it perhaps rather "may he reign one hundred years!"? Possibility of constructing the dative in parallel with the other datives, and then saying "in
                            (his) 15th year"? On this expression, see Sircar’s comments 1963-64: 1-2, and as editor in note at Gai 1963-64: 241. Bühler’s original point about the expression seems important.</note> -->
					          </app>
					          <app loc="6">
						            <lem>cātu<unclear>sāla</unclear>
						            </lem>
						            <note>This word seems to denote a building with rows of
							cells on all
							sides.<!-- According to <https://www.britannica.com/technology/quadrangle-architecture>, the term 'quadrangle', which primarily denotes a quadrangular space,  "is also used to describe the building or building complex that contains" such an area.  -->
							For a ground plan indicating the referent of this
							gift, see <bibl>
								                <ptr target="eiad-bibl:Sarkar1960"/>:
									<citedRange>pl. LXVIII</citedRange>
							              </bibl>.</note>
					          </app>
				        </listApp>
